2
‘5’ is scoped to the read() 
method, 50 it can’t be used 
anywhere else
An instance variable lives 
as long as the object 
does. If the object is still 
alive, 50 are its instance 
variables.
public void read() {
 int 5 = 42;
 // ‘5’ can be used only
 // within this method.
 // When this method ends,
 // ‘5’ disappears completely.
}
public class Life {
 int size;
 public void setSize(int 5) {
 size = 5;
 // ‘5’ disappears at the 
 // end of this method,
 // but ‘size’ can be used
 // anywhere in the class
 }
}
Variable ‘5’ (this time a method parameter) 
is in scope only within the setSize() 
method. But instance variable size is 
scoped to the life of the object as opposed 
to the life of the method.
BAD!! Not legal to 
use ‘5’ here!
The variable ‘5’ is alive, but in scope only within the 
read() method. When sleep() completes and read() is 
on top of the Stack and running again, read() can 
still see ‘5’. When read() completes and is popped off 
the Stack, ‘5’ is dead. Pushing up digital daisies.
sleep() can’t see the ‘5’ variable. Since 
it’5 not in sleep()’5 own Stack frame, 
sleep() doesn’t know anything about it.
